text:
# Monitoring & Telemetry

Qdrant exposes its metrics in [Prometheus](https://prometheus.io/docs/instrumenting/exposition_formats/#text-based-format)/[OpenMetrics](https://github.com/OpenObservability/OpenMetrics) format, so you can integrate them easily with the compatible tools and monitor Qdrant with your own monitoring system. You can use the `/metrics` endpoint and configure it as a scrape target.

Metrics endpoint: <http://localhost:6333/metrics>

The integration with Qdrant is easy to [configure](https://prometheus.io/docs/prometheus/latest/getting_started/#configure-prometheus-to-monitor-the-sample-targets) with Prometheus and Grafana.

text: ## Kubernetes health endpoints  *Available as of v1.5.0*  Qdrant exposes three endpoints, namely [`/healthz`](http://localhost:6333/healthz), [`/livez`](http://localhost:6333/livez) and [`/readyz`](http://localhost:6333/readyz), to indicate the current status of the Qdrant server. These currently provide the most basic status response, returning HTTP 200 if Qdrant is started and ready to be used. Regardless of whether an [API key](https://qdrant.tech/documentation/guides/security/#authentication) is configured, the endpoints are always accessible. You can read more about Kubernetes health endpoints [here](https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/using-api/health-checks/).
